ctivists who condemned the disregard for nature and indigenous communities. In this archival and ethnographic study, Riofrancos expands the study of resource politics by decentering state resource policy and locating it in a field of political struggle populated by actors with conflicting visions of resource extraction. She demonstrates how Ecuador's commodity-dependent economy and history of indigenous uprisings offer a unique opportunity to understand development, democracy, and the ecological foundations of global capitalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEconomic developmentxEnvironmental aspectszEcuador. 0aEnergy policyzEcuador. 0aEnvironmental policyzEcuador. 0aMineral industriesxGovernment policyzEcuador. 0aMineral industriesxPolitical aspectszEcuador. 0aNatural resourcesxPolitical aspectszEcuador. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069631808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478012122zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478012122423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478012122/original  a978-3-11-069631-8  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070473-0  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishb2020  aEBA_DUK_ALL 